The basic idea of bankruptcy is that if you have a company with $1,000 of a=
ssets and $2,000 of liabilities, you can=E2=80=99t pay back everyone everyt=
hing you owe them. You could just pay back the first creditors who show up =
and ask for their money back, until the $1,000 is gone, and then give the r=
emaining creditors zero, but that seems unfair and probably destroys value.
  [1]
 So the bankruptcy system says, essentially, that you get all the creditors=
 together and give them all 50 cents on the dollar. There are tons of nuanc=
es to this =E2=80=94=C2=A0about timing, about seniority, about collateral, =
about restructuring plans and equitization, about avoidable preferences, et=
c. =E2=80=94=C2=A0but that=E2=80=99s the core idea.
There are various extensions. One important one comes in what is called mas=
s tort liability. If you have a company and it sells a lot of products and =
makes a lot of money and then it turns out that one of the products kills p=
eople, they will sue. Juries in the US don=E2=80=99t like it when companies=
 make products that kill people, and they tend to award enormous damages in=
 cases like that. You multiply enormous damages by lots of cases, and you c=
an easily end up with damages that exceed the value of the company. This ca=
n lead to unfair results, not for you =E2=80=94=C2=A0who cares about you =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0but for your victims: If a $1 billion company has killed 100=
 people, the first 10 who sue might get $100 million each of damages, leavi=
ng nothing for the remaining 90.
  [2]
 What you want is some sort of system that is like =E2=80=9Cwe will set up =
a website to collect claims from everyone our product has harmed, and then =
when we have all those claims we will divide up our company=E2=80=99s asset=
s equally among the victims.=E2=80=9D
  [3]

In principle there are various ways you could do that =E2=80=94=C2=A0lawyer=
s could bring one big class action on behalf of everyone harmed by the comp=
any, and then negotiate a global settlement; or lawyers could bring a bunch=
 of class actions and judges could coordinate their cases so everyone gets =
fair treatment; or Congress could  pass new laws=C2=A0setting up payout sch=
edules for victims of the product; etc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0but one pretty pract=
ical approach is bankruptcy. This, after all, is what bankruptcy is for: It=
 is a system to make sure that creditors are all paid fairly out of the ass=
ets of a company, rather than paying some creditors a lot because they are =
early and others nothing because they are too late. The company files for b=
ankruptcy, it sets up a website looking for claims, it adds up all the clai=
ms, and then it divides its assets among the claimants.
  [4]

When=C2=A0do you do that? You have a profitable company, it makes a variety=
 of products that it sells for a lot of money, stuff is good, and then some=
one sues you because one of your products kills people. You go to trial, lo=
se, pay damages. Someone else sues. You go to trial, lose, pay damages. At =
some point these cases get to be too much =E2=80=94=C2=A0they overwhelm the=
 value of your company =E2=80=94=C2=A0and you stop going to trial piecemeal=
; you file for bankruptcy to divide up your assets among the victims. But t=
hen the first victims =E2=80=94=C2=A0the ones who went to trial =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0got paid in full, while the later victims probably don=E2=80=99t: The=
ir recovery in bankruptcy probably ends up being less than it would have be=
en if they had sued first. You have=C2=A0partially=C2=A0solved the problem =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0filing for bankruptcy created some fairness among the later =
claimants =E2=80=94=C2=A0but not entirely, because earlier claimants still =
got more.
The way to solve the problem is to   file for bankruptcy early, when the co=
mpany looks=C2=A0healthy, when it has a lot of money that it can use to pay=
 claims, before it has lost a bunch of lawsuits. The first person sues you,=
 you do an analysis, you find out =E2=80=9Coh yes our product is dangerous =
and will incur a lot of liability and will eventually bankrupt us,=E2=80=9D=
 and you file for bankruptcy immediately to pay everyone fairly.
This is obviously hard to do for a lot of reasons =E2=80=94=C2=A0you don=E2=
=80=99t=C2=A0want=C2=A0to file for bankruptcy, you don=E2=80=99t believe=C2=
=A0that your product kills people or that the damages should be so high, it=
 is hard to=C2=A0predict=C2=A0what claims will bankrupt you, you hope you c=
an grow your way out of the liabilities, etc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0but it is, in =
some very abstract sense, the right analysis.
But what if the claims won=E2=80=99t bankrupt you? What if you are a super =
gigantic company that makes a lot of money selling a lot of products almost=
 none of which kill people, but you do sell one product that kills people a=
nd will lead to billions of dollars of damages? You might be tempted to use=
 the bankruptcy courts anyway. Bankruptcy is=C2=A0good=C2=A0at this, at adj=
udicating claims fairly, at paying people with similar claims similar amoun=
ts, at setting up a website to collect claims and administering them effici=
ently. Even if you have enough money to pay everyone in full, it might just=
 be more practical and efficient to use the mechanisms of bankruptcy rather=
 than litigating each case separately.
Also, let=E2=80=99s be clear, bankruptcy courts don=E2=80=99t have=C2=A0jur=
ies. Bankruptcy courts are run by judges, who are bankruptcy professionals =
and who are used to dealing with companies that are, you know, bankrupt. Th=
ey are used to not having enough money to go around; they are not temperame=
ntally lavish with claims. Regular courts are different. If your product ki=
lls people, one of them might sue you in state court, and a jury might awar=
d them $1 billion of punitive damages to send a message to evil corporation=
s that they should not kill people. A bankruptcy judge is not going to do t=
hat.=C2=A0
So you might want to file for bankruptcy to pay off all your victims fairly=
 and, perhaps, cheaply, even if their claims will not really =E2=80=9Cbankr=
upt=E2=80=9D you in=C2=A0the traditional sense. But in fact that is kind of=
 a drastic step, expensive and disruptive and risky and probably bad for sh=
areholders. No chief executive officer of a big company wants to file for b=
ankruptcy if it is not strictly necessary.
There is a=C2=A0neater approach:
=09You put the liabilities in a box. You create a new subsidiary, you put t=
he product-that-kills-people business in that subsidiary, and you transfer =
the liabilities related to that product to the subsidiary. This is, in gene=
ral, hard to do, but in fact Texas has a =09weird merger law that allows it=
: You can =E2=80=9Cmerge=E2=80=9D your company into two companies, one with=
 the liabilities and one with the rest of the business.=09You have the=C2=
=A0box=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0the new subsidiary with all the product liabilit=
ies =E2=80=94=C2=A0file for bankruptcy. You get fair and consistent adjudic=
ation of the product claims, inside the box, and the rest of the company ju=
st goes along relatively normally.

This is called the =E2=80=9CTexas two-step.=E2=80=9D In its extreme form it=
 sounds like very bad cheating: You can=E2=80=99t really put all the liabil=
ities=C2=A0and none of the money=C2=A0in the box; that is just a way to def=
raud victims, and surely they=E2=80=99d find a way to do something about it=
. But a milder form of the Texas Two-Step is that you put the liabilities i=
n the box, put the box in bankruptcy, but have the parent company guarantee=
=C2=A0its product liabilities. (Perhaps up to some reasonable number, perha=
ps not.) Then you can say =E2=80=9Cno, we are not doing this to get out of =
paying our liabilities; we are doing it to pay them in a fairer and more co=
nsistent way.=E2=80=9D
Johnson & Johnson is a consumer health-care company with a $400 billion mar=
ket capitalization and a broad range of products, most of which are fine. I=
t also makes baby powder, and there are claims =E2=80=94=C2=A0which J&J dis=
putes =E2=80=94=C2=A0that the talc in the baby powder contains traces of as=
bestos and causes cancer. J&J has lost some trials about these claims, and =
been ordered to pay billions of dollars in damages. So it did a Texas two-s=
tep bankruptcy for the talc business.=C2=A0
People who had talc claims objected, arguing that J&J should not be allowed=
 to do this, that it should have to face their talc lawsuits individually i=
n regular trials. The bankruptcy court disagreed, the claimants appealed, a=
nd   yesterday they won:

Johnson & Johnson can=E2=80=99t use bankruptcy to resolve more than 40,000 =
US cancer lawsuits over its now-withdrawn baby powder, a federal appeals co=
urt ruled.=C2=A0
The three-judge panel in Philadelphia sided with cancer victims, who argued=
 J&J wrongly put its specially created unit, LTL Management, under court pr=
otection to block juries around the country from hearing the lawsuits and h=
anding out damage awards.=C2=A0
The ruling means J&J will most likely need to defend itself against claims =
that tainted talc in its baby powder causes cancer. The company has lost a =
number of such cases =E2=80=94 including one that was appealed all the way =
to the US Supreme Court, before J&J was forced to pay more than $2 billion =
to one group of victims.

Here is  the opinion=C2=A0of the US Court of Appeals for the Third Circuit.
  [5]
=C2=A0It describes the Texas two-step:

As the most important step, the merger allocated LTL responsibility for ess=
entially all liabilities of Old Consumer tied to talc-related claims.=C2=A0=
This meant, among other things, it would take the place of Old Consumer in =
current and future talc lawsuits and be responsible for their defense. =E2=
=80=A6
Of the assets Old Consumer passed to LTL, most important were Old Consumer=
=E2=80=99s rights as a payee under the Funding Agreement with J&J and New C=
onsumer. On its transfer, that gave LTL, outside of bankruptcy, the ability=
 to cause New Consumer and J&J, jointly and severally, to pay it cash up to=
 the value of New Consumer for purposes of satisfying any talc-related cost=
s as well as normal course expenses. ... The value of the payment right cou=
ld=C2=A0not drop below a floor defined as the value of New Consumer measure=
d as of the time of the divisional merger, estimated by LTL at $61.5 billio=
n, and was subject to increase as the value of New Consumer increased after=
 it.

That is, LTL =E2=80=94=C2=A0the box where J&J put its talc claims =E2=80=94=
 could draw at least $61.5 billion from J&J to pay off those claims. The po=
int here, the bankruptcy court concluded, was not to keep J&J from having t=
o pay talc claims; the entire value of J&J=E2=80=99s consumer business was =
still on the line for those claims. The point, rather, was to deal with tho=
se claims in an organized and efficient way, to treat all the claimants fai=
rly.
You can see why a bankruptcy court might find that argument appealing: A ba=
nkruptcy judge would tend to think that he is the right person to run an or=
ganized process to resolve lots of claims fairly, since that is after all w=
hat he does all day. But the Third Circuit disagreed, not because it thinks=
 that the bankruptcy court is a bad place to resolve claims, and not becaus=
e it thinks that J&J is avoiding liability with the Texas two-step, but bec=
ause LTL isn=E2=80=99t bankrupt enough:

Good intentions=E2=80=94such as to protect the J&J brand or comprehensively=
 resolve litigation=E2=80=94do not suffice alone. What counts to access the=
 Bankruptcy Code=E2=80=99s safe harbor is to meet its intended=C2=A0purpose=
s. Only a putative debtor in financial distress can do so. LTL was not. =E2=
=80=A6
Our precedents show a debtor who does not suffer from financial distress ca=
nnot demonstrate its Chapter 11 petition serves a valid bankruptcy purpose =
supporting good faith. =E2=80=A6
We cannot agree LTL was in financial distress when it filed its Chapter 11 =
petition. The value and quality of its assets, which include a roughly=C2=
=A0$61.5 billion payment right against J&J and New Consumer, make this hold=
ing untenable. =E2=80=A6
From these facts=E2=80=94presented by J&J and LTL themselves=E2=80=94we can=
 infer only that LTL, at the time of its filing, was highly solvent with ac=
cess to cash to meet comfortably its liabilities as they came due for the f=
oreseeable future. It looks correct to have implied, in a prior court filin=
g, that there was not =E2=80=9Cany imminent or even likely need of [it] to =
invoke the Funding Agreement to its maximum amount or anything close to it.=
=E2=80=9D

That is, LTL =E2=80=94=C2=A0J&J=E2=80=99s box =E2=80=94=C2=A0has plenty of =
money (or, rather, can claim plenty of money from J&J) to pay claims, so it=
 doesn=E2=80=99t need to file for bankruptcy. It can just defend lawsuits a=
s they come in. If it runs out of money =E2=80=94=C2=A0or gets close to run=
ning out of money =E2=80=94=C2=A0then, you know, come back to bankruptcy co=
urt and we=E2=80=99ll talk.
In some ways this is a sensible reading of the bankruptcy code, but it is a=
 little bit of a weird result. The point of doing any of this is to do it e=
arly, before you are out of money, so that you have plenty of money to pay =
all the claimants fairly. The court realizes this awkwardness (citations om=
itted):

We recognize the Code contemplates =E2=80=9Cthe need for early access to ba=
nkruptcy relief to allow a debtor to rehabilitate its business before it is=
 faced with a hopeless situation.=E2=80=9D A =E2=80=9Cfinancially troubled=
=E2=80=9D debtor facing mass tort liability, for example, may require bankr=
uptcy to =E2=80=9Cenable a continuation of [its] business and to maintain a=
ccess to the capital markets=E2=80=9D even before it is insolvent.=C2=A0
Still, encouragement of early filing =E2=80=9Cdoes not open the door to pre=
mature filing.=E2=80=9D This may be a fine line in some cases, but our bank=
ruptcy system puts courts, vested with equitable powers, in the best positi=
on to draw it.

You don=E2=80=99t have to be=C2=A0insolvent=C2=A0to file for bankruptcy, an=
d it is good to file=C2=A0early, but not prematurely. You want to file for =
bankruptcy while you still have plenty of money to pay claims, but not too =
much money.
  [6]
=C2=A0It is a fine line.

