Elsewhere   in bankruptcy:

A court-appointed examiner blasted crypto lender Celsius Network Ltd and it=
s former Chief Executive Officer Alex Mashinsky for lacking adequate risk m=
anagement and misleading customers about its business practices and financi=
al health.=C2=A0
Examiner Shoba Pillay said in her 689-page final report published Tuesday t=
hat Celsius =E2=80=94 which let people earn yield on their coins by lending=
 them out =E2=80=94 lacked the ability to accurately track its assets and l=
iabilities, and tried to erase misrepresentations made by Mashinsky in publ=
ic statements.=C2=A0

Here is  the report, and you might not expect a 689-page report by a lawyer=
 in a bankruptcy case to be entertaining reading, but you=E2=80=99d be wron=
g. (You will probably find it less entertaining if you invested in Celsius.=
) Part of the problem at Celsius was that (1) its business model was bad an=
d (2) it lied about it. The report says:

The business model Celsius advertised and sold to its customers was not the=
 business that Celsius actually operated. Through its website, marketing em=
ails, Twitter, livestream town hall meetings, and other messaging, Celsius =
sold its customers on the concept that it was better than traditional =E2=
=80=9Cbig banks.=E2=80=9D By investing with Celsius, its customers were tol=
d that they would be able to =E2=80=9Cunbank=E2=80=9D themselves and enjoy =
=E2=80=9Cfinancial freedom=E2=80=9D as part of the Celsius community. Celsi=
us emphasized that it put =E2=80=9Cits community first=E2=80=9D and that it=
s business would be =E2=80=9Cbuilt on trust=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Ctranspare=
ncy=E2=80=9D with its community members. Celsius promoted itself as an altr=
uistic organization, bragging in one=C2=A0blog post: =E2=80=9CCan we really=
 bring unprecedented financial freedom, economic opportunity and income equ=
ality to everyone in the world? We are Celsius. We dream big.=E2=80=9D
Celsius boasted that its primary financial product=E2=80=94its =E2=80=9CEar=
n=E2=80=9D program=E2=80=94 was the =E2=80=9Csafest place for your crypto.=
=E2=80=9D Customers who participated in the Earn program transferred their =
crypto assets to Celsius in exchange for interest, or what Celsius called r=
ewards. In turn, Celsius deployed its customers=E2=80=99 crypto assets=E2=
=80=94through further loans, investments, or on exchanges=E2=80=94to genera=
te income, or what Celsius called yield. Celsius=E2=80=99s co-founder and m=
ajority owner, Alex Mashinsky, repeatedly told customers in his weekly live=
stream conversations (referred to as =E2=80=9CAsk Mashinsky Anything=E2=80=
=9D or =E2=80=9CAMAs=E2=80=9D) that customer-deposited coins =E2=80=9Care y=
our coins, not our coins . . . [i]t=E2=80=99s always your Bitcoin.=E2=80=9D=
 When asked what would happen in the event of a bankruptcy, Mr. Mashinsky t=
old customers =E2=80=9Ccoins are returned to their owners even in the case =
of bankruptcy.=E2=80=9D
Celsius advertised that it knew how to generate high returns with low risk =
by doing =E2=80=9Cwhat Celsius does best=E2=80=9D=E2=80=94carefully vetting=
 its financial counterparties and ensuring that when those counterparties b=
orrowed crypto assets from Celsius, they pledged =E2=80=9Cover 100% collate=
ral=E2=80=9D to secure their loans. Celsius sold its customers on the promi=
se that Celsius would pay them =E2=80=9Cat least 5% annual interest=E2=80=
=9D and that their rewards would equal each customer=E2=80=99s share of up =
to 80% of Celsius=E2=80=99s revenues.

Basically none of that was true: =E2=80=9CCelsius did not distribute up to =
80% of its revenues to its customers because it had little to no profits to=
 distribute.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9CCelsius made loans that were not fully secur=
ed or were unsecured so that it could charge higher interest rates.=E2=80=
=9D =E2=80=9CBy June 2021, it was routine for one-third of Celsius=E2=80=99=
s institutional loan portfolio to be wholly unsecured and more than half of=
 the portfolio to be under-collateralized.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9CCelsius did no=
t have a risk=C2=A0management function or written risk policies in place be=
fore 2021.=E2=80=9D And, of course, Celsius=E2=80=99s coins were very much =
not returned to their owners in the case of bankruptcy.
Even worse, though, is the stuff about Celsius=E2=80=99s own CEL token. Cel=
sius created CEL tokens, and sold them for cash to raise money, and also di=
stributed them to insiders (Mashinsky) who sold them for more money; meanwh=
ile Celsius was =E2=80=9Cmarket making=E2=80=9D in Celsius tokens and pushi=
ng up their price. If you squint, what that sentence means is something lik=
e =E2=80=9CCelsius took its customers=E2=80=99 real money and gave it to Ma=
shinsky in exchange for some magic beans.=E2=80=9D I mean, that is an argum=
entative and somewhat extreme way of putting it. On the other hand here are=
 some actual quotes from the bankruptcy report!
During the height of Celsius=E2=80=99s market making, Celsius often sought =
to protect CEL from price drops that it attributed to Mr. Mashinsky=E2=80=
=99s sales of large amounts of his personal CEL holdings. As a result of Mr=
. Mashinsky=E2=80=99s sales, Celsius often increased the size of its restin=
g orders to buy all of the CEL that Mr. Mashinsky and his other companies w=
ere selling. These trades caused Celsius=E2=80=99s former Chief Financial O=
fficer to write =E2=80=9C[w]e are talking about becoming=C2=A0a regulated e=
ntity and we are doing something possibly illegal and definitely not compli=
ant.=E2=80=9D As one employee noted in an internal Slack communication: =E2=
=80=9Cif anyone ever found out our position and how much our founders took =
in USD could be a very very bad look . . . We are using users USDC to pay f=
or employees worthless CEL . . . All because the company is the one inflati=
ng the price to get the valuations to be able to sell back to the company.=
=E2=80=9D
Yeesh! And:
In 2022, Celsius employees routinely discussed that CEL was =E2=80=9Cworthl=
ess,=E2=80=9D stating that its price =E2=80=9Cshould be 0,=E2=80=9D and tha=
t Celsius should =E2=80=9Cassume CEL is $0 since we cannot liquidate our cu=
rrent CEL position,=E2=80=9D and questioning whether any party (other than =
Celsius itself) was purchasing CEL.
And:
In April 2022, Celsius=E2=80=99s Coin Deployment Specialist described Celsi=
us=E2=80=99s practice of =E2=80=9Cusing customer stable coins=E2=80=9D and =
=E2=80=9Cgrowing short in customer coins=E2=80=9D to buy CEL as =E2=80=9Cve=
ry ponzi like.=E2=80=9D A few weeks later when Celsius made another push to=
 prop up the price of CEL, Celsius=E2=80=99s former Vice President of Treas=
ury asked where the cash was coming from to make the CEL=C2=A0purchases and=
 Celsius=E2=80=99s Coin Deployment Specialist replied, =E2=80=9Cusers like =
always.=E2=80=9D This same employee explained that at the time he made this=
 statement, Celsius had =E2=80=9Cnegative equity=E2=80=9D and therefore nec=
essarily was using customer funds when it made these purchases.
Aaaaahhhh! You can=E2=80=99t! You can=E2=80=99t send messages like that! If=
 you find yourself messaging your boss to say things like =E2=80=9Cour busi=
ness is very Ponzi like=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cwe have negative equity so we=
=E2=80=99re using customer funds to buy worthless coins so our founder can =
cash out,=E2=80=9D no! Stop! If you have written sentences like that, don=
=E2=80=99t send them to your boss! Print them out and get yourself a lawyer=
