<table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">J&amp;J</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The basic idea of bankruptcy is that if you ha=
ve a company with $1,000 of assets and $2,000 of liabilities, you can=E2=80=
=99t pay back everyone everything you owe them. You could just pay back the=
 first creditors who show up and ask for their money back, until the $1,000=
 is gone, and then give the remaining creditors zero, but that seems unfair=
 and probably destroys value.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-=
1" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom=
-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !impor=
tant; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a> So the bankruptcy system says, essentially, that you get all the credi=
tors together and give them all 50 cents on the dollar. There are tons of n=
uances to this =E2=80=94=C2=A0about timing, about seniority, about collater=
al, about restructuring plans and equitization, about avoidable preferences=
, etc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0but that=E2=80=99s the core idea.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There are various extensions. One important on=
e comes in what is called mass tort liability. If you have a company and it=
 sells a lot of products and makes a lot of money and then it turns out tha=
t one of the products kills people, they will sue. Juries in the US don=E2=
=80=99t like it when companies make products that kill people, and they ten=
d to award enormous damages in cases like that. You multiply enormous damag=
es by lots of cases, and you can easily end up with damages that exceed the=
 value of the company. This can lead to unfair results, not for you =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0who cares about you =E2=80=94=C2=A0but <em>for your victims</em>: =
If a $1 billion company has killed 100 people, the first 10 who sue might g=
et $100 million each of damages, leaving nothing for the remaining 90.<a cl=
ass=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-2" style=3D"color: #000000; text-d=
ecoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: =
#000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparen=
t !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a> What you want is some sort of system that is like =E2=80=9Cwe will set=
 up a website to collect claims from everyone our product has harmed, and t=
hen when we have all those claims we will divide up our company=E2=80=99s a=
ssets equally among the victims.=E2=80=9D<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=
=3D"#footnote-3" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important;=
 border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-styl=
e: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inli=
ne-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In principle there are various ways you could =
do that =E2=80=94=C2=A0lawyers could bring one big class action on behalf o=
f everyone harmed by the company, and then negotiate a global settlement; o=
r lawyers could bring a bunch of class actions and judges could coordinate =
their cases so everyone gets fair treatment; or Congress could <a href=3D"h=
ttps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30414414.272006/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3=
cuY29uZ3Jlc3MuZ292L2NvbmdyZXNzaW9uYWwtcmVwb3J0LzEwOHRoLWNvbmdyZXNzL3NlbmF0Z=
S1yZXBvcnQvMTE4LzE/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB35436117" itemprop=3D"StoryLink=
" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-d=
ecoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: =
#000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> pass new law=
s</a>=C2=A0setting up payout schedules for victims of the product; etc. =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0but one pretty practical approach is bankruptcy. This, after al=
l, is what bankruptcy is for: It is a system to make sure that creditors ar=
e all paid fairly out of the assets of a company, rather than paying some c=
reditors a lot because they are early and others nothing because they are t=
oo late. The company files for bankruptcy, it sets up a website looking for=
 claims, it adds up all the claims, and then it divides its assets among th=
e claimants.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-4" style=3D"color=
: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bord=
er-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-=
color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[4]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><em>When=C2=A0</em>do you do that? You have a =
profitable company, it makes a variety of products that it sells for a lot =
of money, stuff is good, and then someone sues you because one of your prod=
ucts kills people. You go to trial, lose, pay damages. Someone else sues. Y=
ou go to trial, lose, pay damages. At some point these cases get to be too =
much =E2=80=94=C2=A0they overwhelm the value of your company =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0and you stop going to trial piecemeal; you file for bankruptcy to divide=
 up your assets among the victims. But then the first victims =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0the ones who went to trial =E2=80=94=C2=A0got paid in full, while the la=
ter victims probably don=E2=80=99t: Their recovery in bankruptcy probably e=
nds up being less than it would have been if they had sued first. You have=
=C2=A0<em>partially=C2=A0</em>solved the problem =E2=80=94=C2=A0filing for =
bankruptcy created some fairness among the later claimants =E2=80=94=C2=A0b=
ut not entirely, because earlier claimants still got more.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The way to solve the problem is to <a href=3D"=
https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30414414.272006/aHR0cHM6Ly93d=
3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMTItMjMvdGhlLXB1cmR1ZS1i=
YW5rcnVwdGN5LWRpZG4tdC13b3JrP2NtcGlkPUJCRDAxMzEyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWR=
pdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMDEzMSZ1dG1fY2FtcG=
FpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB35dedf40" itemprop=3D"StoryLi=
nk" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text=
-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color=
: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  file for =
bankruptcy <em>early</em></a>, when the company looks=C2=A0<em>healthy</em>=
, when it has a lot of money that it can use to pay claims, before it has l=
ost a bunch of lawsuits. The first person sues you, you do an analysis, you=
 find out =E2=80=9Coh yes our product is dangerous and will incur a lot of =
liability and will eventually bankrupt us,=E2=80=9D and you file for bankru=
ptcy immediately to pay everyone fairly.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is obviously hard to do for a lot of reas=
ons =E2=80=94=C2=A0you don=E2=80=99t=C2=A0<em>want=C2=A0</em>to file for ba=
nkruptcy, you don=E2=80=99t <em>believe=C2=A0</em>that your product kills p=
eople or that the damages should be so high, it is hard to=C2=A0<em>predict=
=C2=A0</em>what claims will bankrupt you, you hope you can grow your way ou=
t of the liabilities, etc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0but it is, in some very abstract =
sense, the right analysis.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But what if the claims <em>won=E2=80=99t </em>=
bankrupt you? What if you are a super gigantic company that makes a lot of =
money selling a lot of products almost none of which kill people, but you d=
o sell one product that kills people and will lead to billions of dollars o=
f damages? You might be tempted to use the bankruptcy courts anyway. Bankru=
ptcy is=C2=A0<em>good=C2=A0</em>at this, at adjudicating claims fairly, at =
paying people with similar claims similar amounts, at setting up a website =
to collect claims and administering them efficiently. Even if you have enou=
gh money to pay everyone in full, it might just be more practical and effic=
ient to use the mechanisms of bankruptcy rather than litigating each case s=
eparately.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Also, let=E2=80=99s be clear, bankruptcy court=
s don=E2=80=99t have=C2=A0<em>juries</em>. Bankruptcy courts are run by jud=
ges, who are bankruptcy professionals and who are used to dealing with comp=
anies that are, you know, bankrupt. They are used to not having enough mone=
y to go around; they are not temperamentally lavish with claims. Regular co=
urts are different. If your product kills people, one of them might sue you=
 in state court, and a jury might award them $1 billion of punitive damages=
 to send a message to evil corporations that they should not kill people. A=
 bankruptcy judge is not going to do that.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So you might want to file for bankruptcy to pa=
y off all your victims fairly and, perhaps, cheaply, even if their claims w=
ill not really =E2=80=9Cbankrupt=E2=80=9D you in=C2=A0the traditional sense=
. But in fact that is kind of a drastic step, expensive and disruptive and =
risky and probably bad for shareholders. No chief executive officer of a bi=
g company wants to file for bankruptcy if it is not strictly necessary.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There is a=C2=A0neater approach:</p>
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: disc; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You put the liabilities in a box. You =
create a new subsidiary, you put the product-that-kills-people business in =
that subsidiary, and you transfer the liabilities related to that product t=
o the subsidiary. This is, in general, hard to do, but in fact Texas has a =
<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30414414.272006/aH=
R0cHM6Ly9zdGF0dXRlcy5jYXBpdG9sLnRleGFzLmdvdi9Eb2NzL0JPL2h0bS9CTy4xMC5odG0/6=
07f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB155e3038" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"items=
cope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !imp=
ortant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bott=
om-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=09weird merger law</a> that allo=
ws it: You can =E2=80=9Cmerge=E2=80=9D your company into two companies, one=
 with the liabilities and one with the rest of the business.</li>=09<li sty=
le=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You have the=C2=A0<em>box=C2=A0</em>=E2=80=94=C2=
=A0the new subsidiary with all the product liabilities =E2=80=94=C2=A0file =
for bankruptcy. You get fair and consistent adjudication of the product cla=
ims, inside the box, and the rest of the company just goes along relatively=
 normally.</li>
</ul>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is called the =E2=80=9C<a href=3D"https:/=
/link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30414414.272006/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxv=
b21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDctMjAvYmlsbC1hY2ttYW4tcy10aHJ=
lZS1zcGFjcy13ZXJlLXRvby1tYW55P2NtcGlkPUJCRDAxMzEyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZW=
RpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMDEzMSZ1dG1fY2Ftc=
GFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB2661d746" itemprop=3D"StoryL=
ink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; tex=
t-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-colo=
r: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Texas two-=
step</a>.=E2=80=9D In its extreme form it sounds like very bad cheating: Yo=
u can=E2=80=99t really put all the liabilities=C2=A0<em>and none of the mon=
ey</em>=C2=A0in the box; that is just a way to defraud victims, and surely =
they=E2=80=99d find a way to do something about it. But a milder form of th=
e Texas Two-Step is that you put the liabilities in the box, put the box in=
 bankruptcy, but have the parent company <em>guarantee=C2=A0</em>its produc=
t liabilities. (Perhaps up to some reasonable number, perhaps not.) Then yo=
u can say =E2=80=9Cno, we are not doing this to <em>get out of </em>paying =
our liabilities; we are doing it to pay them in a fairer and more consisten=
t way.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Johnson &amp; Johnson is a consumer health-car=
e company with a $400 billion market capitalization and a broad range of pr=
oducts, most of which are fine. It also makes baby powder, and there are cl=
aims =E2=80=94=C2=A0which J&amp;J disputes =E2=80=94=C2=A0that the talc in =
the baby powder contains traces of asbestos and causes cancer. J&amp;J has =
lost some trials about these claims, and been ordered to pay billions of do=
llars in damages. So it did a Texas two-step bankruptcy for the talc busine=
ss.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">People who had talc claims objected, arguing t=
hat J&amp;J should not be allowed to do this, that it should have to face t=
heir talc lawsuits individually in regular trials. The bankruptcy court dis=
agreed, the claimants appealed, and <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergb=
usiness.com/click/30414414.272006/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL=
2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDEtMzAvai1qLWNhbi10LXVzZS1iYW5rcnVwdGN5LXRvLWVuZC1jYW5j=
ZXItc3VpdHMtYXBwZWFscy1jb3VydC1zYXlzP2NtcGlkPUJCRDAxMzEyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV=
0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMDEzMSZ1dG=
1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBd6d7bee8" itemprop=3D=
"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0000=
00; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bott=
om-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  y=
esterday they won</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Johnson &amp; Johnson can=E2=80=99t use bankru=
ptcy to resolve more than 40,000 US cancer lawsuits over its now-withdrawn =
baby powder, a federal appeals court ruled.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The three-judge panel in Philadelphia sided wi=
th cancer victims, who argued J&amp;J wrongly put its specially created uni=
t, LTL Management, under court protection to block juries around the countr=
y from hearing the lawsuits and handing out damage awards.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The ruling means J&amp;J will most likely need=
 to defend itself against claims that tainted talc in its baby powder cause=
s cancer. The company has lost a number of such cases =E2=80=94 including o=
ne that was appealed all the way to the US Supreme Court, before J&amp;J wa=
s forced to pay more than $2 billion to one group of victims.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here is <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomberg=
business.com/click/30414414.272006/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cyLmNhMy51c2NvdXJ0cy5nb3Yv=
b3BpbmFyY2gvMjIyMDAzcC5wZGY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB271cc10f" itemprop=3D"=
StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #00000=
0; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-botto=
m-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> the=
 opinion</a>=C2=A0of the US Court of Appeals for the Third Circuit.<a class=
=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-5" style=3D"color: #000000; text-deco=
ration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #00=
0000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !=
important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[5]</span>
</a>=C2=A0It describes the Texas two-step:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">As the most important step, the merger allocat=
ed LTL responsibility for essentially all liabilities of Old Consumer tied =
to talc-related claims.=C2=A0This meant, among other things, it would take =
the place of Old Consumer in current and future talc lawsuits and be respon=
sible for their defense. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Of the assets Old Consumer passed to LTL, most=
 important were Old Consumer=E2=80=99s rights as a payee under the Funding =
Agreement with J&amp;J and New Consumer. On its transfer, that gave LTL, ou=
tside of bankruptcy, the ability to cause New Consumer and J&amp;J, jointly=
 and severally, to pay it cash up to the value of New Consumer for purposes=
 of satisfying any talc-related costs as well as normal course expenses. ..=
. The value of the payment right could=C2=A0not drop below a floor defined =
as the value of New Consumer measured as of the time of the divisional merg=
er, estimated by LTL at $61.5 billion, and was subject to increase as the v=
alue of New Consumer increased after it.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That is, LTL =E2=80=94=C2=A0the box where J&am=
p;J put its talc claims =E2=80=94 could draw at least $61.5 billion from J&=
amp;J to pay off those claims. The point here, the bankruptcy court conclud=
ed, was not to keep J&amp;J from having to pay talc claims; the entire valu=
e of J&amp;J=E2=80=99s consumer business was still on the line for those cl=
aims. The point, rather, was to deal with those claims in an organized and =
efficient way, to treat all the claimants fairly.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">You can see why a bankruptcy court might find =
that argument appealing: A bankruptcy judge <em>would </em>tend to think th=
at he is the right person to run an organized process to resolve lots of cl=
aims fairly, since that is after all what he does all day. But the Third Ci=
rcuit disagreed, not because it thinks that the bankruptcy court is a bad p=
lace to resolve claims, and not because it thinks that J&amp;J is avoiding =
liability with the Texas two-step, but because LTL isn=E2=80=99t bankrupt e=
nough:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Good intentions=E2=80=94such as to protect the=
 J&amp;J brand or comprehensively resolve litigation=E2=80=94do not suffice=
 alone. What counts to access the Bankruptcy Code=E2=80=99s safe harbor is =
to meet its intended=C2=A0purposes. Only a putative debtor in financial dis=
tress can do so. LTL was not. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Our precedents show a debtor who does not suff=
er from financial distress cannot demonstrate its Chapter 11 petition serve=
s a valid bankruptcy purpose supporting good faith. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We cannot agree LTL was in financial distress =
when it filed its Chapter 11 petition. The value and quality of its assets,=
 which include a roughly=C2=A0$61.5 billion payment right against J&amp;J a=
nd New Consumer, make this holding untenable. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">From these facts=E2=80=94presented by J&amp;J =
and LTL themselves=E2=80=94we can infer only that LTL, at the time of its f=
iling, was highly solvent with access to cash to meet comfortably its liabi=
lities as they came due for the foreseeable future. It looks correct to hav=
e implied, in a prior court filing, that there was not =E2=80=9Cany imminen=
t or even likely need of [it] to invoke the Funding Agreement to its maximu=
m amount or anything close to it.=E2=80=9D</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That is, LTL =E2=80=94=C2=A0J&amp;J=E2=80=99s =
box =E2=80=94=C2=A0has plenty of money (or, rather, can claim plenty of mon=
ey from J&amp;J) to pay claims, so it doesn=E2=80=99t need to file for bank=
ruptcy. It can just defend lawsuits as they come in. If it runs out of mone=
y =E2=80=94=C2=A0or gets close to running out of money =E2=80=94=C2=A0then,=
 you know, come back to bankruptcy court and we=E2=80=99ll talk.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In some ways this is a sensible reading of the=
 bankruptcy code, but it is a little bit of a weird result. The point of do=
ing any of this is to do it early, before you are out of money, so that you=
 have plenty of money to pay all the claimants fairly. The court realizes t=
his awkwardness (citations omitted):</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We recognize the Code contemplates =E2=80=9Cth=
e need for early access to bankruptcy relief to allow a debtor to rehabilit=
ate its business before it is faced with a hopeless situation.=E2=80=9D A =
=E2=80=9Cfinancially troubled=E2=80=9D debtor facing mass tort liability, f=
or example, may require bankruptcy to =E2=80=9Cenable a continuation of [it=
s] business and to maintain access to the capital markets=E2=80=9D even bef=
ore it is insolvent.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Still, encouragement of early filing =E2=80=9C=
does not open the door to premature filing.=E2=80=9D This may be a fine lin=
e in some cases, but our bankruptcy system puts courts, vested with equitab=
le powers, in the best position to draw it.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">You don=E2=80=99t have to be=C2=A0<em>insolven=
t=C2=A0</em>to file for bankruptcy, and it is good to file=C2=A0<em>early</=
em>, but not <em>prematurely</em>. You want to file for bankruptcy while yo=
u still have plenty of money to pay claims, but not too much money.<a class=
=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-6" style=3D"color: #000000; text-deco=
ration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #00=
0000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !=
important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[6]</span>
</a>=C2=A0It is a fine line.</p>
