<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Celsius!</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Elsewhere <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombe=
rgbusiness.com/click/30414414.272006/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZX=
dzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDEtMzEvY2Vsc2l1cy1leGFtaW5lci1yaXBzLWludG8tY3J5cHRvL=
WxlbmRlci1pbi1oZXItZmluYWwtcmVwb3J0P2NtcGlkPUJCRDAxMzEyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0=
bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMDEzMSZ1dG1=
fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBf77d9cb3" itemprop=3D"=
StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #00000=
0; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-botto=
m-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  in=
 bankruptcy</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A court-appointed examiner blasted crypto lend=
er Celsius Network Ltd and its former Chief Executive Officer Alex Mashinsk=
y for lacking adequate risk management and misleading customers about its b=
usiness practices and financial health.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Examiner Shoba Pillay said in her 689-page fin=
al report published Tuesday that Celsius =E2=80=94 which let people earn yi=
eld on their coins by lending them out =E2=80=94 lacked the ability to accu=
rately track its assets and liabilities, and tried to erase misrepresentati=
ons made by Mashinsky in public statements.=C2=A0</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here is <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomberg=
business.com/click/30414414.272006/aHR0cHM6Ly9jYXNlcy5zdHJldHRvLmNvbS9wdWJs=
aWMveDE5MS8xMTc0OS9QTEVBRElOR1MvMTE3NDkwMTMxMjM4MDAwMDAwMDAzOS5wZGY/607f07c=
eef4b8524a319a23cB28f24689" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" =
target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important=
; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-sty=
le: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> the report</a>, and you might not expe=
ct a 689-page report by a lawyer in a bankruptcy case to be entertaining re=
ading, but you=E2=80=99d be wrong. (You will probably find it less entertai=
ning if you invested in Celsius.) Part of the problem at Celsius was that (=
1) its business model was bad and (2) it lied about it. The report says:</p=
>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The business model Celsius advertised and sold=
 to its customers was not the business that Celsius actually operated. Thro=
ugh its website, marketing emails, Twitter, livestream town hall meetings, =
and other messaging, Celsius sold its customers on the concept that it was =
better than traditional =E2=80=9Cbig banks.=E2=80=9D By investing with Cels=
ius, its customers were told that they would be able to =E2=80=9Cunbank=E2=
=80=9D themselves and enjoy =E2=80=9Cfinancial freedom=E2=80=9D as part of =
the Celsius community. Celsius emphasized that it put =E2=80=9Cits communit=
y first=E2=80=9D and that its business would be =E2=80=9Cbuilt on trust=E2=
=80=9D and =E2=80=9Ctransparency=E2=80=9D with its community members. Celsi=
us promoted itself as an altruistic organization, bragging in one=C2=A0blog=
 post: =E2=80=9CCan we really bring unprecedented financial freedom, econom=
ic opportunity and income equality to everyone in the world? We are Celsius=
. We dream big.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Celsius boasted that its primary financial pro=
duct=E2=80=94its =E2=80=9CEarn=E2=80=9D program=E2=80=94 was the =E2=80=9Cs=
afest place for your crypto.=E2=80=9D Customers who participated in the Ear=
n program transferred their crypto assets to Celsius in exchange for intere=
st, or what Celsius called rewards. In turn, Celsius deployed its customers=
=E2=80=99 crypto assets=E2=80=94through further loans, investments, or on e=
xchanges=E2=80=94to generate income, or what Celsius called yield. Celsius=
=E2=80=99s co-founder and majority owner, Alex Mashinsky, repeatedly told c=
ustomers in his weekly livestream conversations (referred to as =E2=80=9CAs=
k Mashinsky Anything=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9CAMAs=E2=80=9D) that customer-depo=
sited coins =E2=80=9Care your coins, not our coins . . . [i]t=E2=80=99s alw=
ays your Bitcoin.=E2=80=9D When asked what would happen in the event of a b=
ankruptcy, Mr. Mashinsky told customers =E2=80=9Ccoins are returned to thei=
r owners even in the case of bankruptcy.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Celsius advertised that it knew how to generat=
e high returns with low risk by doing =E2=80=9Cwhat Celsius does best=E2=80=
=9D=E2=80=94carefully vetting its financial counterparties and ensuring tha=
t when those counterparties borrowed crypto assets from Celsius, they pledg=
ed =E2=80=9Cover 100% collateral=E2=80=9D to secure their loans. Celsius so=
ld its customers on the promise that Celsius would pay them =E2=80=9Cat lea=
st 5% annual interest=E2=80=9D and that their rewards would equal each cust=
omer=E2=80=99s share of up to 80% of Celsius=E2=80=99s revenues.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Basically none of that was true: =E2=80=9CCels=
ius did not distribute up to 80% of its revenues to its customers because i=
t had little to no profits to distribute.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9CCelsius made lo=
ans that were not fully secured or were unsecured so that it could charge h=
igher interest rates.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9CBy June 2021, it was routine for on=
e-third of Celsius=E2=80=99s institutional loan portfolio to be wholly unse=
cured and more than half of the portfolio to be under-collateralized.=E2=80=
=9D =E2=80=9CCelsius did not have a risk=C2=A0management function or writte=
n risk policies in place before 2021.=E2=80=9D And, of course, Celsius=E2=
=80=99s coins were very much not returned to their owners in the case of ba=
nkruptcy.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Even worse, though, is the stuff about Celsius=
=E2=80=99s own CEL token. Celsius created CEL tokens, and sold them for cas=
h to raise money, and also distributed them to insiders (Mashinsky) who sol=
d them for more money; meanwhile Celsius was =E2=80=9Cmarket making=E2=80=
=9D in Celsius tokens and pushing up their price. If you squint, what that =
sentence means is something like =E2=80=9CCelsius took its customers=E2=80=
=99 real money and gave it to Mashinsky in exchange for some magic beans.=
=E2=80=9D I mean, that is an argumentative and somewhat extreme way of putt=
ing it. On the other hand here are some actual quotes from the bankruptcy r=
eport!</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">During the height of Celsius=E2=80=
=99s market making, Celsius often sought to protect CEL from price drops th=
at it attributed to Mr. Mashinsky=E2=80=99s sales of large amounts of his p=
ersonal CEL holdings. As a result of Mr. Mashinsky=E2=80=99s sales, Celsius=
 often increased the size of its resting orders to buy all of the CEL that =
Mr. Mashinsky and his other companies were selling. These trades caused Cel=
sius=E2=80=99s former Chief Financial Officer to write =E2=80=9C[w]e are ta=
lking about becoming=C2=A0a regulated entity and we are doing something pos=
sibly illegal and definitely not compliant.=E2=80=9D As one employee noted =
in an internal Slack communication: =E2=80=9Cif anyone ever found out our p=
osition and how much our founders took in USD could be a very very bad look=
 . . . We are using users USDC to pay for employees worthless CEL . . . All=
 because the company is the one inflating the price to get the valuations t=
o be able to sell back to the company.=E2=80=9D</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Yeesh! And:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In 2022, Celsius employees routine=
ly discussed that CEL was =E2=80=9Cworthless,=E2=80=9D stating that its pri=
ce =E2=80=9Cshould be 0,=E2=80=9D and that Celsius should =E2=80=9Cassume C=
EL is $0 since we cannot liquidate our current CEL position,=E2=80=9D and q=
uestioning whether any party (other than Celsius itself) was purchasing CEL=
.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In April 2022, Celsius=E2=80=99s C=
oin Deployment Specialist described Celsius=E2=80=99s practice of =E2=80=9C=
using customer stable coins=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cgrowing short in customer=
 coins=E2=80=9D to buy CEL as =E2=80=9Cvery ponzi like.=E2=80=9D A few week=
s later when Celsius made another push to prop up the price of CEL, Celsius=
=E2=80=99s former Vice President of Treasury asked where the cash was comin=
g from to make the CEL=C2=A0purchases and Celsius=E2=80=99s Coin Deployment=
 Specialist replied, =E2=80=9Cusers like always.=E2=80=9D This same employe=
e explained that at the time he made this statement, Celsius had =E2=80=9Cn=
egative equity=E2=80=9D and therefore necessarily was using customer funds =
when it made these purchases.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Aaaaahhhh! You can=E2=80=99t! You can=E2=80=99=
t send messages like that! If you find yourself messaging your boss to say =
things like =E2=80=9Cour business is very Ponzi like=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9C=
we have negative equity so we=E2=80=99re using customer funds to buy worthl=
ess coins so our founder can cash out,=E2=80=9D no! Stop! If you have writt=
en sentences like that, don=E2=80=99t send them to your boss! Print them ou=
t and get yourself a lawyer and a whistle-blower deal! My lord.=C2=A0This i=
s not legal advice but what are you even doing?</p>
