<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusin=
ess.com/click/30414414.272006/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL=
2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMTItMjIvZnR4LWZyaWVuZHMtZmxpcC1vbi1zYmY_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDEz=
MTIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXR=
tX3Rlcm09MjMwMTMxJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB=
93f1c2b3" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" =
style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-wi=
dth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgro=
und-color: #ccc;"> talked last month</a> about AMC Entertainment Holdings I=
nc.=E2=80=99s clever APE trade. Basically AMC is in the business of selling=
 tons of stock, but it ran out of stock to sell: Its corporate charter only=
 authorizes it to issue 524,173,073 common shares, and it had issued pretty=
 much all of them. It went to its shareholders and asked them to vote to am=
end the charter and allow more shares, but it couldn=E2=80=99t get enough v=
otes, mostly because it has so many retail shareholders and retail sharehol=
ders tend not to vote their shares.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So it issued new=C2=A0<em>preferred=C2=A0</em>=
shares, called APEs, that are meant to have similar rights to its regular c=
ommon shares. In particular, the APE shares get to vote alongside the commo=
n shares. In the beginning, AMC issued one free APE share for each common s=
hare =E2=80=94=C2=A0like a stock split, where each share was split into one=
 common share and one APE =E2=80=94=C2=A0but then it started selling APEs f=
or cash too. So now there are more APEs than common shares.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The APEs trade at a huge discount to the commo=
n shares, because they are weird, but AMC can fix that: It will once again =
ask shareholders to vote to authorize more shares, so it can convert the AP=
Es into common shares. But this time, it expects the vote to go better, bec=
ause it is asking not for a vote of common shares but for a <em>combined=C2=
=A0</em>vote of common shares and APEs.=C2=A0Hedge funds and other professi=
onal investors have bought APEs (and perhaps shorted common shares) to bet =
on their prices converging; those investors will be sure to vote their APE =
shares, because that=E2=80=99s what will make the prices converge. (When AP=
Es convert into common shares, the prices will have to mechanically converg=
e.) And there are more APEs (which trade at a discount and would benefit by=
 authorizing more shares) than common shares (which trade at a higher price=
 than the APEs and might lose from convergence). And AMC actually placed a =
big block of APE shares with a hedge fund back in December, and the hedge f=
und agreed to vote in favor of the share authorization.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Last week AMC formally proposed to authorize m=
ore shares; here is <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/clic=
k/30414414.272006/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzE0M=
TE1NzkvMDAwMTEwNDY1OTIzMDA3NTUwL3RtMjMyNzAwLTFfcHJlMTRhLmh0bQ/607f07ceef4b8=
524a319a23cB554fdf48" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=
=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: so=
lid; background-color: #ccc;">the proxy statement</a>. So far it <a href=3D=
"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30414414.272006/aHR0cHM6Ly93=
d3cud3NqLmNvbS9hcnRpY2xlcy9hbWNzLXR3by1lcXVpdHktc2VjdXJpdGllcy1iZWdpbi10by1=
jb252ZXJnZS1hZnRlci1zaGFyZWhvbGRlci1wcm9wb3NhbC1yZWxlYXNlZC0xMTY3NTEwMDY0Nz=
9tb2Q9aXRwX3dzaiZydT15YWhvbw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBeb2f719f" itemprop=3D=
"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0000=
00; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bott=
om-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">see=
ms to be working</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">AMC Entertainment Holdings Inc.=E2=80=99s two =
classes of equity securities came closer to converging Monday after the mov=
ie-theater company disclosed details of the proposals shareholders will vot=
e on at its next shareholder meeting.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">AMC Preferred Equity Units, or =E2=80=9CApes,=
=E2=80=9D closed Monday at $2.33, up 21%, while the company=E2=80=99s commo=
n shares closed at $5.01, down 9%, after the company said that on March 14 =
it plans to hold votes on proposals to convert all outstanding Ape units in=
to common shares, do a 10-for-1 reverse stock split and substantially incre=
ase the number of common shares it will be able to issue in the future.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The proposed transactions could provide a pote=
ntial lifeline for AMC by giving the company more options to raise cash. AM=
C has been struggling with weak box-office results affecting the cinema ind=
ustry, while its shares have sunk close to where they were trading before t=
he company caught fire as a meme stock in early 2021.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Since AMC emerged as a fan favorite among indi=
vidual investors, some of whom refer to themselves as =E2=80=9Capes,=E2=80=
=9D the company tried twice to get shareholder approval to enable it to iss=
ue more common shares, but failed both times due to shareholders=E2=80=99 c=
oncerns regarding dilution. ...</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CGiven that Ape unit holders essential=
ly control the vote at 64% of combined holdings and may not get another cha=
nce to extract value from those units, we expect the two proposals to pass =
and for this vote to open the door to a massive equity raising opportunity =
for the company in the coming years,=E2=80=9D said Eric Wold, an analyst at=
 B. Riley Securities.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I guess this is technically allowed,<a class=
=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-7" style=3D"color: #000000; text-deco=
ration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #00=
0000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !=
important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[7]</span>
</a>=C2=A0and I find it rather clever, though I suppose you might think it=
=E2=80=99s cheating. There is something a little unseemly about a company t=
rying to issue more shares, failing to get shareholder approval because the=
 shareholders worry about dilution, and solving the problem by issuing many=
 more shares at lower prices in order to get the votes to approve more shar=
es. As a matter of corporate finance it seems like the right move, but as a=
 matter of shareholder relations it is a little rough.</p>
